      "fun_fact": "This pastel was acquired by the Cleveland Museum of Art in the same year as several other works by Redon, leading arts writers to describe Cleveland as holding the most important works by the artist outside of Paris at the time.",
      "digital_description": "Although he was known early in his career for works primarily in black and white, such as charcoal drawings and lithographs, Odilon Redon turned to more colorful media, including pastel, later on. In particular, he focused on commissioned pastel portraits of women with flowers, such as this one. Here, the young niece of the Parisian collector Marcel Kapferer appears alongside colorful blossoms as she looks forward, focused as if in the dreamlike state evoked by her surroundings.",
      "wall_description": "Like the lithographic portraits in this gallery, this pastel demonstrates a shift in Odilon Redon’s late work toward representing recognizable sitters. In this exceptionally large and finished drawing, he depicted the niece of Parisian collector Marcel Kapferer alongside a flowing backdrop of colorful blossoms. The young woman gazes forward, as if in the dreamlike state of her surroundings. When Kapferer sold the drawing in 1926 through New York City’s Kraushaar Galleries, an important vendor of contemporary art at the time, the museum was able to acquire it within just months of obtaining Redon’s <em>Orpheus,</em> seen nearby.",
