      "fun_fact": "Another version of this pastel (now in the collection of the Musée Fabre de Montpellier) was part of a group of later works by Redon shown at the 1913 International Exhibition of Modern Art—better known as the Armory Show—which introduced the artist to American audiences.",
      "digital_description": "Drawn in vivid layers of pastel crayon, this work depicts the head of the poet and musician Orpheus. The story of the god of music, whose music carried on after his death through his lyre and head, fascinated Redon, who related to Orpheus's dedication to his art. The subject also aligned with Redon's broader interest in dreams and spirituality around this time and he represented Orpheus several times throughout his career, in various media. Here, the god's head floats as if in stasis while Mount Parnassus—the home of Apollo and the Muses—soars from behind.",
      "wall_description": "Considered by Odilon Redon to be one of his greatest works in any media, this drawing portrays the head of the mythical god of music. Redon contrasted powdery purple and ochre pastel to represent the figure’s head and lyre, through which Orpheus’s music carried on after his death. An alternative version of the work was included in the 1913 Armory Show—regarded as the first American exhibition of modern art—where it captured the attention of Cleveland Museum of Art curator William Milliken. When this drawing became available at auction, the museum’s early supporters banded together to raise funds; the acquisition attracted international press attention.",
